<HEADLINE>
<P>
SENATE CANDIDATES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Republican Michael Huffington moved from Texas to California just three years 
ago, purchasing a congressional seat for $5 million, and immediately started 
running for the U.S. Senate. 
</P>
<P>
 Huffington, the ultimate opportunist, has nothing to say about his own 
accomplishments as a member of the Congress, instead resorting to distorting 
Democratic incumbent Sen. Dianne Feinstein's record. 
</P>
<P>
 He should win a chutzpah award for complaining about her tax payments, while 
refusing to release his own tax returns. What's he hiding? 
</P>
<P>
 Dianne Feinstein has represented California well, and her effectiveness is 
unusual for someone with just two years in the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
 Rep. Huffington can buy as many television ads as he likes, but he has yet to 
show why he can do better than Sen. Feinstein, except in one area: misleading 
the voters. 
</P>
<P>
 BILL COLLINS 
</P>
<P>
 Davis 
</P>
<P>
 Turning health care reform into a political football is not only symbolic of 
Washington gamesmanship but carries the potential of a contorted and 
irresponsible legislative process. 
</P>
<P>
 The current campaign for a Senate seat between Feinstein and Huffington 
promises to be a bloody battle along these lines ("Huffington Ad Blasts 
Feinstein's Shift on Health Care," June 18). 
</P>
<P>
 It is interesting that recently, in response to a letter I wrote to Feinstein 
on another subject, she enclosed a brochure supporting President Clinton's 
health plan. Since this was after removing her name as co-sponsor of this 
reform bill, it seems the California senator is trying to have it both ways! 
</P>
<P>
 JESSIE ADAMS 
</P>
<P>
 Wilsonville, Ore. 
</P>
