<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORLD CUP USA '94 / THE FIRST ROUND; SPOTLIGHT; TOO IMPORTANT TO FIGHT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The World Cup has been able to do something the United Nations hasn't in 
Rwanda: create a cease fire in the country where some 200,000 have died in a 
war that began April 6. 
</P>
<P>
 Children play soccer in refugee camps amid the thud of mortar fire and 
delivery of casualties, but when the World Cup is on television -- particularly 
when the game involves Rwandan favorite Nigeria -- the guns fall silent. 
</P>
<P>
 "I wonder if both sides aren't doing the same thing," said U.N. commander Maj. 
Gen. Romeo Dalliare, "powering up generators and watching football instead of 
fighting for a while. We could use more of that in Kigali." 
</P>
</TEXT>
