<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: VENTURA; CITY TO START TALKS ON WATER SYSTEMS LINK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CONSTANCE SOMMER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The city of Ventura has become the first of five major water suppliers in 
Ventura County to endorse a plan to discuss linking the area's disparate water 
systems. 
</P>
<P>
 Stung by the drought a few years ago and alarmed by the earthquake in January, 
the major purveyors say they want to consider linking their water systems with 
neighbors in order to share in times of emergency. 
</P>
<P>
 The Ventura council voted 4 to 0 Monday to allow city officials to begin 
discussions with officials from the other agencies. Calleguas Municipal Water 
District has approved the discussions in concept, but has been waiting for at 
least one other agency to sign off on it before formally approving the talks, 
said Donald Kendall, the agency's general manager. Calleguas is a wholesaler 
that distributes water to Moorpark, Simi Valley, Thousand Oaks, Camarillo and 
Oxnard. 
</P>
<P>
 The United Water Conservation District, which replenishes water in underground 
basins beneath the Oxnard Plain, and which supplies drinking water to Port 
Hueneme, is scheduled to discuss the issue in July. 
</P>
<P>
 The Casitas Municipal Water District, which supplies parts of the Ojai Valley 
and western Ventura, will also consider the topic at its board meeting next 
month. 
</P>
<P>
 Oxnard's City Council will debate the subject sometime this summer. The city 
of Oxnard supplies local water mixed with water from Calleguas to its 
residents. CONSTANCE SOMMER 
</P>
</TEXT>
