<P>
EAST VALLEY FOCUS: SYLMAR; CLASS TO HELP COPE WITH LIFE IN L.A. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JEFF SCHNAUFER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A seminar to help adults and children deal with natural disasters and crime 
will be held through Los Angeles Mission College's Community Extension program. 
</P>
<P>
 "Coping With Living in L.A." will be held between 6:30 and 9 p.m. July 7 at 
Granada Hills High School. 
</P>
<P>
 Taught be Tarzana psychotherapist Teri Ansel, the class is aimed at people who 
feel depressed, anxious, helpless or overwhelmed by everything from earthquakes 
to neighborhood crime. 
</P>
<P>
 Enrollment in the seminar, which costs $26, can be done by telephone or in 
person between 8 a.m. and 6 p.m. Monday through Thursday and from 8 a.m. to 5 
p.m. Friday in the Community Extension office. 
</P>
<P>
 The office is in Veterans Memorial Park, 13000 Sayre St., Sylmar. For more 
information, call (818) 364-7387. JEFF SCHNAUFER 
